    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-11_page01.jpg"/>
                
                <dateline>
                    <date when="1842-11"></date></dateline>
             
                <p>
                    <note>Nov <unclear>26</unclear></note> 1842<lb/>
                    <note>65</note><lb/>
                    Here is the irreverend<lb/>
                    scrap that your reverend<lb/>
                    daughter has handed me with<lb/>
                    an air, to write to you upon<lb/>
                    my dearest <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">mother</persName><lb/></p>
                <p>
                    I have no objection in life to<lb/>
                    dirty notes but I do not want<lb/>
                    dirty or clean here - Keep<lb/>
                    them for me - if they belong to me<lb/>
                    but I thought we had settled<lb/>
                    that you were <hi rend="underline">not</hi>to pay me my<lb/>
                    Quarter Div<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>due July 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> if that<lb/>
                    is what you are talking of<lb/></p>
                <p>
                    I see before me this<lb/>
                    instant an entry in my book<lb/>
                    shewing that you paid me<lb/>
                    Aug<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>13 10<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>that Quarter -} 85 .. 7 . 8<lb/>
                    by <del>draft</del><add><unclear>codicdal</unclear></add> <add><unclear>lodged on Balls -}</unclear></add><lb/>
                    And that I paid you in cash - 21.. 12.. 4<lb/>
                    making up my House acct 107 . 0 . 0<lb/>
                    quarter due Sep<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>-<lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                    So what you are now talking<lb/>
                    of my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeF2">Madam</persName> about notes due<lb/>
                    to me dirty or clean I do not know<lb/>
                    - But shall be very glad to have<lb/>
                    any due &amp; honestly mine - only you keep<lb/>
                    them till we meet on the 21<hi rend="superscript">st</hi>. Prox <del></del><lb/></p>
                
                <p>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#RalsG1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Ralstones</persName> is a most <choice> 
                    <orig>touch<lb/>
                     ing</orig>
                     <reg>touching</reg>
                    </choice>
                    manly letter - I had written<lb/>
                    to him before breakfast this morn<hi rend="superscript">g</hi><lb/>
                    and found his letter on your<lb/>
                    cover when I came down - I shall send it as<lb/>
                    it was truly written - I am afraid you did not<lb/>
                    read <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>rs Moores</persName> characteristic &amp; really ex letter I<lb/>
                    return it therefore - I will<lb/>
                
                <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Bodleian_702_1842-11_page02.jpg"/>
                    answer what you are pleased<lb/>
                    to call <hi rend="underline">the politest note I ever<lb/>
                    received</hi> - polite enough I<lb/>
                    grant - but the polit<hi rend="underline">est!</hi> Oh<lb/>
                    - exaggeration -<lb/>
                    I shall refer him to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HallX2">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi> Hall</persName> <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                    for my part I can have no objection<lb/>
                    to republishing him, what has been<lb/>
                    published &amp; the <hi rend="underline">truths</hi> which<lb/>
                    every one knows! - What is modesty<lb/>
                    those who have it may answer<lb/>
                    &amp; throw the first stone.<lb/></p>
                <p>
                    Thank you my dear for your<lb/>
                    history of Dole's delights - and <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FoxM1" cert="low">Marys</persName><lb/>
                    which delighted your affectionately<lb/>
                    very much <lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">ME</persName><lb/> </p> 
               
                    <postscript><p>
                    The carriage is coming at eleven<lb/>
                    (&amp; it is now I do not know how much<lb/>
                    passed <del>eleven</del> ten) to carry us to<lb/>
                    <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Black-Castle_IE">Black Castle</placeName> by appointment<lb/>
                    Morning vis - paid a very <choice> 
                    <orig>agree<lb/>
                    able</orig>
                    <reg>agreeable</reg>
                    </choice>
                    Vis yester morn &amp; rather evening<lb/>
                    after luncheon bagged, to <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HarrX5">Lady Harriet<unclear>Knowles</unclear></persName><lb/>
                    &amp; knew that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxF3">Rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>Frank</persName> old boy is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#XxxxF3">Frank</persName><lb/>
                    My cidevant Creditor - not a word about<lb/>
                    vile trash - quite full of wit and classics<lb/>
                    &amp; regrets that he <unclear></unclear><lb/>
                    &amp; <unclear></unclear> that he <unclear>never</unclear><lb/>
                    a regular classical Ed<hi rend="superscript">n</hi>.<lb/>
                    and the more <choice> 
                    <orig>enter<lb/>
                    taining</orig>
                    <reg>entertaining</reg>
                    </choice>
                    he is for being<lb/>
                    quite inconsistent in<lb/>
                    all he says &amp; does -<lb/>
                    The most <unclear>decousee</unclear><lb/>
                    mind &amp; conversation<lb/><lb/>
                    you can conceive<lb/></p>
                    <p>
                        
                    Mica of ability -<lb/>
                    glittering thin brittle<lb/>
                    lamina or <unclear>no</unclear><lb/>
                    thats all - told many<lb/>
                    things which if ascertained<lb/>
                    to be facts w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>be interesting<lb/>
                    and curious - But at every<lb/>
                    <unclear>close</unclear>or pause <persName ref="./Personography.xml#FowlX1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Fowler</persName><lb/>
                    rev<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> husband of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HarrX5">Lady<lb/>
                    Harriet</persName>, asked<lb/>
                    Where did you hear that<lb/>
                    Frank - Where did you speak<lb/>
                    up <hi rend="underline">that</hi> <unclear><persName ref="./Personography.xml#SaunX1">Saunderson</persName></unclear><lb/></p>
                        
                    <p>
                    For instance he<lb/>
                    told of a poisonous acre<lb/>
                    near <unclear>athboy</unclear> on which cattle<lb/>
                    infallibly lose their hoofs &amp;<lb/>
                    their horns &amp; on which the potatoes that grow are reported to<lb/>
                    be poisonous<lb/></p>
                 </postscript>

                   
                

                    
                
            </div>
